2_0	0.19240416	&UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR; &QL; Cocaine addicts looking to get clean may want to turn to needles for help.
2_1	0.29691773	A new study by Yale University researchers says acupuncture is an effective treatment for cocaine abuse.
2_2	0.17296899	The finding gives the ancient Chinese remedy a much-needed foothold in Western medicine, experts say, because it's based on a well-controlled clinical study from a major American medical school.
2_3	0.23315609	A report on the finding appears in the latest issue of the Archives of Internal Medicine.
2_4	0.135016	Although the work might be the first large, controlled trial of acupuncture for cocaine addiction, it's not the first time anyone has used the treatment for substance abuse.
2_5	0.12090609	Indeed, some 1,000 clinics worldwide offer the needle therapy for the symptoms of cocaine withdrawal, including nearly 175 in New York state alone, says Dr.
2_6	0.073692269	Michael Smith, a pioneer in the field.
2_7	0.098204325	Smith, a Cornell University psychiatrist who has been practicing acupuncture at Lincoln Hospital in the Bronx for nearly two decades, calls the Yale research ``a very well-documented report with high standards that shows that acupuncture helps reduce the craving for cocaine''.
2_8	0.10505149	The study, led by Yale psychologist Arthur Margolin, looked at the effectiveness of acupuncture in 82 heroin and cocaine addicts who were getting methadone for the first habit but nothing for the second.
2_9	0.07593314	Margolin and his colleagues split the subjects into three groups.
2_10	0.10303414	The first received eight weeks of standard addiction acupuncture therapy, based on guidelines from the National Acupuncture Detoxification Association, which calls for three to five needles placed at specific points in the outer ear.
2_11	0.084818479	The second group had sham needles placed in non-therapeutic sites on the ear.
2_12	0.072868518	The third group watched relaxing videos.
2_13	0.081567062	Urine tests for cocaine were taken three times a week over the trial's two-month period, during which all patients received counseling and group therapy.
2_14	0.13986045	By the last week of the trial, nearly 54 percent of the patients in the acupuncture group had cocaine-free urine, compared with 23 percent of those in the sham needle group and only 9 percent of those who watched videos.
2_15	0.097355505	``This was a highly active placebo arm and we still found an effect over and above that,'' says Margolin, who notes that the effect of acupuncture was as good as that from drug treatment for cocaine addiction.
2_16	0.087145336	HOW IT WORKS STILL A MYSTERY While the latest work suggests that acupuncture helps control cravings for cocaine, it doesn't say anything about why it succeeds.
2_17	0.084909449	``Quite honestly, we don't know why it works,'' Margolin says.
2_18	0.095749658	``We're just beginning to look in Western terms'' at the biological mechanism behind acupuncture's effect.
2_19	0.096957751	Smith, however, says tests show that the needles, if properly placed, restore balance to the body's electrical currents.
2_20	0.089134476	``Acupuncture helps the body help itself''.
2_21	0.089253518	Still, he admits, no one really understands the full mechanics of this assistance.
2_22	0.093044759	Whatever the reason, Margolin and Smith agree that acupuncture alone isn't a sufficient treatment for addiction, be it to cocaine, alcohol, tobacco or other substances.
2_23	0.11041963	``This is a treatment that helps a person participate in all the other treatments we have,'' such as counseling and group therapy, Smith says.
2_24	0.095333352	In fact, by law, ear acupuncture for addicts can only be performed in the context of a licensed drug-treatment program that includes these other methods, he says.
2_25	0.095240706	However, acupuncture does have a key advantage over counseling, Smith says.
2_26	0.090513698	If addicts refuse to acknowledge their drug cravings, therapists have little recourse to treat them.
2_27	0.097256276	But with acupuncture, he says, addicts can get treated without losing face.
2_28	0.08799304	``You can treat a problem that the patient doesn't admit to''.
2_29	0.120868	Barbara Mitchell, a licensed acupuncturist and executive director of the Acupuncture and Oriental Medicine Alliance in Olalla, Wash.
2_30	0.08479722	, says the Yale research lends an extra measure of credibility to the practice.
2_31	0.091827938	On the other hand, Mitchell says, with an estimated 15,000 licensed acupuncturists in the United States already, the field is well on its way to becoming mainstream.
2_32	0.10250524	Many insurance companies now reimburse for the treatment, which got a major shot in the arm in 1997 when the National Institutes of Health held a consensus conference to discuss the scientific validity of needle therapy.
2_33	0.091439715	That report found that acupuncture helped control pain from dental procedures, menstruation and other conditions, with fewer side effects than conventional remedies, Mitchell says.
